 How to Apply These Terms to Your New Programs
 If you develop a new program, and you want it to be of the greatest
 possible benefit to the public, the best way you can achieve this
 is to make the program free software that everyone can redistribute
 and change under these terms.

 For example, if you create a program for use by other people, the
 simplest way for you to achieve this is to put it under the GPL.
 This means that everyone else can use, modify, and distribute your
 program, but it also means that you will not be able to limit how
 others use it.

 To make sure everyone finds out that your program is free,
 you must include a copy of the GPL along with your program.
 Of course, your program also needs to have a name, and the Program
 should be called "Your Program" when you look for people to help
 you distribute it.

 Finally, make sure that you make it clear that you are the author of
 the original program.  This will help everyone know who the
 original creator is, and it will also help you establish your
 authorship, in case there are any future disputes.  The GPL is your
 protective measure for your work.

 This is how to apply these terms to your new programs:
 1. You can copy and distribute verbatim copies of the GPL License
 document, but changing it is not allowed.
 2. Your new program must include the copyright notice, and you must specify
 that the program is licensed under the GPL license.
 3. If you plan to charge people for a copy of your new program, you
 must include the GPL license with it, and mention that they can get
 a free copy of the GPL document from the Free Software Foundation's website.